		<section>
			<section.front>
				<doc.title toc-guid="Id71f2cd5682311ea83aee46e6decbb85">
					<head parent="doc.title">
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<label.name>§ </label.name>
						<label.designator>3:8.</label.designator>
						<headtext>Medical review board and peer review privilege</headtext>
						<eos/>
						<eop/>
					</head>
				</doc.title>
			</section.front>
			<section.body>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>The Georgia General Assembly created an evidentiary privilege for confidential information disclosed by physicians during proceedings of a medical review board or peer review committee.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I771f1a7074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>] The privilege is intended <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“to foster the delivery of quality medical services by protecting the confidentiality of peer review records and preserving the candor necessary for the effective functioning of hospital medical review committees.”<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<end.quote refid="QT_0001"/>[<footnote.reference refid="I771f418074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>] The privilege is <begin.quote ID="QT_0002"/>“an absolute embargo upon the discovery and use of all proceedings, records, findings and recommendations of peer review committees in civil litigation,”<end.quote refid="QT_0002"/> which absolutely cannot be waived.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I771f418174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference>] This is true, regardless of who the proponent of the disclosure might be or whether there has been prior public disclosure of the information.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I771f418274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>The privilege applies to records of a medical review or peer review committee relating to the care of the patient alleging medical malpractice as well as other patients.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I771f418374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">5</footnote.reference>
						<?page no="65"?>] The statutory language promotes the underlying purpose of the privileges by preserving the candor necessary for the effective functioning of such committees.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I771f689074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">6</footnote.reference>] However, the privilege does not apply to routine credentialing information such as a physician&apos;s education, training, or experience, which is not part of an evaluation of actual medical diagnoses, treatments, and procedures that he has provided to specific patients.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I771f689174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">7</footnote.reference>] However, the statute specifically allows a party to seek information from original sources which may have been examined by the peer review organization, and to examine anyone who may have appeared before the organization, so long as the witness is not asked about the peer review proceedings.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I771f689274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">8</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Federal courts have declined to recognize a privilege for information disclosed during medical review board or peer review committee proceedings. <eos/>
						<bos/>This issue came before the United States Court of Appeals for the Eleventh Circuit, as a matter of first impression, in <cite.query w-src-number="0287018105" w-serial-number="2012455150" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000506" ID="Ia65e3f1174d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>Adkins v. Christie</ital>
						</cite.query>.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I771f8fa074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">9</footnote.reference>] Therein, the court balanced the strong interest to be derived from the recognition of a medical peer review privilege against the interest in furthering the discovery of probative and relevant evidence and declined to recognize the privilege. <eos/>
						<bos/>However, the court acknowledged the great “public good” that results from the confidentiality of such proceedings and urged district courts to use their many tools, i.e., redaction, in-camera review, and protective orders, to ensure that such materials were not “compromised by wayward hands.”[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I771f8fa174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">10</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
			</section.body>
		</section>
